== Overview == In postwar studies of medieval {{ill|Buddhism in Japan|ja|日本仏教史|Buddhism in Japan=Buddhism in Japan|lt=Buddhist history of Japan|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buddhism in Japan|qq=}}, the dominant view was that the old Buddhist schools, the [[:en:Nanto Rokushū|Six Nanto Schools]] and the {{ill|Two Heian Schools|ja|平安二宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Two Heian Schools|qq=}} ([[:en:Tiantai|Tendai]] and [[:en:Shingon Buddhism|Shingon]]), existed in a '''mutually exclusive or oppositional''' relationship.
In contrast, Kuroda introduced the term '''Kenmitsu (顕密)'''—which at the time referred to all of Buddhism—as a conceptual framework and proposed the '''Kenmitsu System Theory (顕密体制論)'''.
According to Kuroda, the '''orthodox religion''' in medieval Japan was '''Kenmitsu Buddhism''', which had been integrated '''around [[:en:Mikkyō|Esoteric Buddhism]]''' (密教) since the '''[[Heian period]]'''. The Eight Traditional Buddhist Schools were '''not separate entities''' but functioned within '''a competitive yet unified order''', based on '''a common foundation of esoteric rituals and mystical faiths focused on pacification and incantations'''. Within this system, Esoteric Buddhism (密教) was considered the '''absolute and universal truth'''. Temples of the '''old Buddhist schools''', such as [[:en:Enryaku-ji|Enryaku-ji]], maintained '''close ties to state power''', solidifying their position as '''the legitimate religious institutions''' throughout the medieval period. This state of affairs is what Kuroda termed the '''Kenmitsu System'''.
This theory challenged the '''postwar perception''' that saw the {{ill|Kamakura Buddhism|lt=Kamakura Buddhism|lt=Kamakura New Buddhism|ja|鎌倉新仏教|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura New Buddhism|qq=}} '''(鎌倉新仏教)''' as the '''main representative of medieval Buddhism''', instead emphasizing that '''the old Buddhist schools were the true mainstream of medieval Japanese Buddhism'''. Additionally, by incorporating '''Buddhism into the broader framework of political and social history''', Kuroda's theory—built upon his earlier '''{{ill|Kenmon System Theory|ja|権門体制論|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenmon System Theory|qq=}} (権門体制論)'''—introduced '''a new perspective on Buddhist history'''.
