'''Kenmitsu System''' (顕密体制, Kenmitsu Taisei) is a theory proposed by historian {{ill|Toshio Kuroda (Shinto professor)|en|Toshio Kuroda (Shinto professor)|qid=Q7827765|lt=Toshio Kuroda|1=Toshio Kuroda (Shinto professor)}} regarding the religious system of medieval {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. It was introduced in the book *The Medieval Japanese State and Religion* (『日本中世の国家と宗教』), published by {{ill|Iwanami Shoten|en|Iwanami Shoten|qid=Q1331427|lt=Iwanami Shoten|1=Iwanami Shoten}} in {{ill|1975|en|1975|qid=Q2479|lt=1975|1=1975}}, under the title *The Development of the Kenmitsu System in the Middle Ages*.

== Overview ==
In postwar studies of medieval {{ill|Buddhism in Japan|ja|日本仏教史|Buddhism in Japan=Buddhism in Japan|lt=Buddhist history of Japan|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buddhism in Japan|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 日本の仏教|1=Buddhism in Japan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q736311}}, the dominant view was that the old Buddhist schools, the {{ill|Nanto Rokushū|en|Nanto Rokushū|qid=Q5366159|lt=Six Nanto Schools|1=Nanto Rokushū}} and the {{ill|Two Heian Schools|ja|平安二宗|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Two Heian Schools|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 平安仏教|1=Heian Buddhism|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11482387}} ({{ill|Tiantai|en|Tiantai|qid=Q668188|lt=Tendai|1=Tiantai}} and {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|en|Shingon Buddhism|qid=Q550182|lt=Shingon|1=Shingon Buddhism}}), existed in a '''mutually exclusive or oppositional''' relationship.

In contrast, Kuroda introduced the term '''Kenmitsu (顕密)'''—which at the time referred to all of Buddhism—as a conceptual framework and proposed the '''Kenmitsu System Theory (顕密体制論)'''.

According to Kuroda, the '''orthodox religion''' in medieval Japan was '''Kenmitsu Buddhism''', which had been integrated '''around {{ill|Mikkyō|en|Mikkyō|qid=Q336102|lt=Esoteric Buddhism|1=Mikkyō}}''' (密教) since the '''{{ill|Heian period|en|Heian period|qid=Q193292|lt=Heian period|1=Heian period}}'''. The Eight Traditional Buddhist Schools were '''not separate entities''' but functioned within '''a competitive yet unified order''', based on '''a common foundation of esoteric rituals and mystical faiths focused on pacification and incantations'''. Within this system, Esoteric Buddhism (密教) was considered the '''absolute and universal truth'''. Temples of the '''old Buddhist schools''', such as {{ill|Enryaku-ji|en|Enryaku-ji|qid=Q917195|lt=Enryaku-ji|1=Enryaku-ji}}, maintained '''close ties to state power''', solidifying their position as '''the legitimate religious institutions''' throughout the medieval period. This state of affairs is what Kuroda termed the '''Kenmitsu System'''.

This theory challenged the '''postwar perception''' that saw the {{ill|Kamakura Buddhism|lt=Kamakura Buddhism|lt=Kamakura New Buddhism|ja|鎌倉新仏教|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura New Buddhism|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 鎌倉仏教}} '''(鎌倉新仏教)''' as the '''main representative of medieval Buddhism''', instead emphasizing that '''the old Buddhist schools were the true mainstream of medieval Japanese Buddhism'''. Additionally, by incorporating '''Buddhism into the broader framework of political and social history''', Kuroda's theory—built upon his earlier '''{{ill|Kenmon System Theory|ja|権門体制論|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenmon System Theory|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 権門体制}} (権門体制論)'''—introduced '''a new perspective on Buddhist history'''.

